## Exascale Discretizations

The Center for Efficient Exascale Discretizations (CEED) is an [Exascale
Computing Project (ECP)](http://exascaleproject.org) co-design center focused on
the following goals:

- Help applications leverage future architectures by providing them with
  [state-of-the-art discretization algorithms](ceed-code.md) that better exploit
  the hardware and deliver a significant performance gain over conventional
  methods.

- Learn from and educate hardware vendors and software technologies projects
  about efficient finite element algorithms through CEED-developed [proxies and
  miniapps](miniapps.md).

- Provide an efficient and user-friendly unstructured PDE discretization
  component for the future [exascale software ecosystem](ceed-code.md).

CEED is a research partnership involving [30+ computational scientists](about.md)
from two DOE labs and and five universities centered around the following
computational motifs and their performance on exascale hardware:

#### PDE-based simulations on unstructured grids

Including general finite element algorithms on triangular, quadrilateral, tetrahedral and hexahedral meshes in 1D, 2D and 3D,
support for the whole de Rham complex: H1, H(curl), H(div) and L2/DG spaces and discretizations,
conforming and non-conforming unstructured AMR, and
pptimized assembly support for low-order methods.

#### High-order/spectral finite elements
Anyorder space on any order mesh, hh-order conforming and non-conforming curved meshesm, and eficient matrix-free operator evaluation on all mesh geometries for all spaces in the de Rham complex.

The CEED team includes members of the [Nek5000](nek.md), [MFEM](mfem.md), [MAGMA](magma.md), [OCCA](occa.md) and [PETSc](petsc.md) projects.
Building on these efforts, the co-design center will produce a range of [software products](software.md) co-design efforts by collaborating in [four interconnected R&D thrusts](thrusts.md).

